  "doc_id": "6577",
  "text": "For decades, sedation for endoscopy has almost exclusively been given by the endoscopist. With an increasing demand for complex diagnostic and therapeutic procedures in patients with greater comorbidities, alternatives to the benzodiazepine/ opioid conscious sedation model are required. 33 34 There is also a cost to having little or no alternative to conscious sedation. As a means to ensure a comfortable patient (and so allowing the procedure to be completed), the national BSG audit reported that 33% of patients undergoing ERCP received more than 5.5 mg of midazolam. As a result, 8% required a reversal with flumazenil and/or naloxone. [CITATION_1] Conversely, the inability to safely provide sufficient sedation using conscious sedation results in 40% of patients reporting pain or discomfort during ERCP. [CITATION_2] Intolerance of sedation contributes to more than 30% of failed ERCPs performed under conscious sedation. 4 36 Tolerability of double balloon enteroscopy has also been reported to be poor despite high doses of sedation given. [CITATION_3] As a means to complete a required therapeutic procedure, how often is 'conscious' sedation given to a deeper level of sedation, which should involve an anaesthetist?",
